<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>

<section xml:id="SQ8" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Absolute Convergence (SQ8)</title>
    <objectives>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <xi:include href="outcomes/08.ptx"/>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>
    
    <activity>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                
                Consider the series: <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n}{n}</m>.
                
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <p>
                Does the series <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n}{n}</m> converge or diverge?  (Recall <xref ref="fact-SQ8alternatingSeriesTest"/>.)
            </p>
        </task>
        
        <task>
            <p>
                Does the series <m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \left|\frac{(-1)^n}{n}\right|</m> converge or diverge?  (Recall <xref ref="activity-SQ5harmonicSeries"/>.)
            </p>
        </task>
    </activity>
    
    
    <definition xml:id="definition-absoluteconvergence">
        <p>
            Given a series <me>\sum a_n</me> we say that <m>\displaystyle \sum a_n</m> is <em>absolutely convergent</em> if <m>\displaystyle \sum |a_n|</m> converges.
        </p>
    </definition>
    
    <activity>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Consider the following series:
                <ol>
                    <li><m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{n^2(-1)^n}{n^3+1}</m>.</li>
                    <li><m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{n^2}</m>.</li>
                    <li><m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty (-1)^n \left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^n</m>.</li>
                    <li><m>\displaystyle \sum_{n=1}^\infty -n</m>.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <p>For each of the series, determine if the series converges using any method.</p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p>For each of the series, compute <m>|a_n|</m>.</p>
        </task>
        <task>
            <p>For each of the series, determine if the series is <em>absolutely convergent</em>.</p>
        </task>
    </activity>
    
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                If you know a series <m>\displaystyle \sum a_n</m> is absolutely convergent, what can you conclude about whether or not <m>\displaystyle \sum a_n</m> is convergent?
                
                <ol>
                    <li>We cannot determine if <m>\displaystyle \sum x_n</m> is convergent.</li>
                    <li><m>\displaystyle \sum x_n</m> is convergent since it <q>grows slower</q> than <m>\displaystyle \sum |x_n|</m> (and falls slower than <m>\displaystyle \sum -|x_n|</m>).</li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    
    
    <fact>
        If <m>\displaystyle \sum a_n</m> is absolutely convergent, then it must be convergent.
    </fact>
    
    
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Find 3 series that are convergent but not absolutely convergent (recall <xref ref="fact-SQ8alternatingSeriesTest"/>, <xref ref="SQ6"/>).
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    
    
    
    
</section>
